{{Infobox person | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1999|9|24}} | birth_place = [[Terek, Kabardino-Balkar Republic|Terek]], [[Kabardino-Balkaria]], [[Russia]] | nationality = Russian | known_for = World's heaviest child }} '''Dzhambulat "Dzhambik" Khatokhov''' (born 24 September 1999) is the world's heaviest child since 2003, according to the [[Guinness Book of Records]].<ref name=NMN>{{cite web|url=http://nnm.ru/blogs/bombrik/dzhambulat_hatohov_samyiy_bolshoiy_rebenok_na_planete/|title=The biggest kid on the planet|date=9 June 2008|accessdate=17 June 2010|language=Russian|publisher=NMN Russia}}</ref>
==Biography== At the age of eight, Dzhambik and his mother visited [[Japan]] to be part of a television program, "Impossible", on [[Fuji Television]].<ref name="NMN" /> His mother, Nelya Kabardarkova, who lives comfortably because of her son's fame, has denied all accusations of fuelling his growth and says she is encouraging Dzhambik's wish to become a [[sumo|sumo wrestler]].<ref name=SUN>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/features/2543601/Dzhambik-Khatokhov-weighs-over-23-stone-and-is-just-nine-years-old.html|title=23 stone age nine|date=20 July 2009|publisher=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|accessdate=25 January 2010|location=London|first=Oliver|last=Harvey}}</ref> Dzhambik also attends sumo battles. In 2003, he wrestled Georgy Bibilauri, another large teenager in the [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] capital [[Tbilisi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2003/07/10/national/main562632.shtml|title=The Odd Truth|date=3 July 2003|accessdate=17 June 2010|publisher=[[CBS News]]}}</ref> By the age of nine, Dzhambik weighted {{Convert|146.1|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.
Doctors are unsure of the cause of his fast growth. In 2008, the [[United Kingdom|British]] doctor Ian Campbell,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mymultiplesclerosis.co.uk/misc/jambik.html|title=The world's biggest boy|date=8 October 2013|access-date=16 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101102111253/http://mymultiplesclerosis.co.uk/misc/jambik.html|archive-date=2 November 2010|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> one of the world's leading experts in obesity, visited Dzhambik and performed a series of tests on him at a [[Moscow]] clinic where he is treated every year for his [[obesity]].<ref name="NMN" /> The tests showed that 9 year old Dzhambik's bones were the size of an average 13-year-old boy. He was also tested for [[anabolic steroids]], which can cause abnormal bone growth, but the results were negative. As shown on an episode of ''Body Shock'', Campbell and other health care professionals urged Dzambik's mother to help the boy eat a better diet and lose weight to improve his health, but Nelya rejected their advice and insisted the boy was healthy and capable of becoming a [[sumo]] wrestler or other sportsman. In 2006, journalist Nick Patton Walsh wrote in ''The Guardian'' that Nelya demanded money in order for him to meet Dzambik; Walsh hestitated as such payments were against ''Guardian'' policy but eventually relented, paying £160 or about 8000 rubles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/may/26/russia.health|title=I like to be big|date=26 May 2006|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=15 June 2010|location=London}}</ref>
Dzhambik's size has earned him the nickname [[Sosruko]] after an ancient hero from local mythology. Sosruko was a giant, a fierce warrior who protected his people and embodied qualities people in the [[Caucasus]] greatly respect: strength and size. According to Nelya Kabardarkova, her son's grandfather was also known as a [[Bogatyr]], a Russian word for a sort of gentle giant.
Dzhambik has appeared on many Russian TV Shows, but gained world recognition through the UK Channel 4 series [[BodyShock]] in the episode "''World's Biggest Boy''"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/bodyshock/episode-guide/series-7/episode-1|title=World's biggest boy|date=26 November 2008|accessdate=25 January 2010|publisher=[[Channel 4]]}}</ref> which aired on many TV channels around the world.
