:''For the poker personality, see [[Matt Savage (poker director)]]. For the keyboardist/actor see [[Levellers (band)]].'' {{Infobox musical artist | name = Matt Savage | image = Matt Savage, 2005.jpg | image_size = | landscape = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank --> | alt = | caption = Savage in 2005 | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | birth_name = | alias = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1992|5|12}} | birth_place = [[Sudbury, Massachusetts|Sudbury]], [[Massachusetts]], United States | origin = | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) --> | death_place = | genre = {{flatlist|*[[Jazz]] *[[Classical music|Classical]] }} | occupation = Musician, composer, teacher | instrument = [[Piano]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]] | years_active = <!-- YYYY–YYYY (or –present) --> | label = | associated_acts = | website = {{URL|http://www.savagerecords.com/}} }} '''Matthew "Matt" Savage''' (born May 12, 1992) is an [[United States|American]] [[autistic savant]] [[musician]]. Born in [[Sudbury, Massachusetts|Sudbury]], [[Massachusetts]],<ref name=JSF>Pine, Dan. [http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/27046/edition_id/518/format/html/displaystory.html "Autistic jazz prodigy already playing with greats"], ''The Jewish News Weekly of Northern California'', 16 September 2005</ref> he is the son of Diane and Lawrence "Larry" Savage.<ref name=geochamp>Morrow, Marsha. https://web.archive.org/web/20060514114802/http://www.mledger.com/2004/archives/1_news_040804.shtml "N.H. geography champ"] ''[[Monadnock Ledger]]'', 8 April 2004. (cached webpage)</ref>
== Background == Savage was a precocious infant who walked early and learned to read by the age of 18 months.<ref name=SavantsDSC>''Savants'', [[Discovery Channel]] documentary, 2003.</ref> He was diagnosed with [[pervasive developmental disorder]], a form of [[autism]], at age three.<ref>Jones, Chad. [http://www.insidebayarea.com/bayarealiving/ci_3049622 "13-year-old Matt Savage has autism and a genius for jazz"], ''InsideBayArea.com'', 21 September 2005.</ref> He did not like any noises or music during his early childhood.<ref name=Wired>Silberman, Steve. [https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/11.12/genius.html "The Key to Genius"], ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]], December 2003, page 229.</ref>
At age six, Savage taught himself to read [[piano]] music.<ref name=projo>Massimo, Rick. [http://www.projo.com/music/content/projo_20051023_savage.31f5de3.html "N.H. pianist, 13, considers autism one of his strengths"], ''[[Providence Journal]]'', 23 October 2005.</ref> He studied [[European classical music|classical]] piano for less than a year before discovering [[jazz]], which became his main focus.
He and his younger sister, Kitty, were both [[home schooling|home schooled]].<ref name=geochamp /> He began studying at the [[New England Conservatory of Music]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Massachusetts]] in the fall of 1999. He continued his classical studies as well.
Among Savage's talents are [[hyperlexia]]<ref name=JSF /> and [[Absolute pitch|perfect pitch]].<ref name=NPRATC>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1142280 "Pianist Matt Savage"], ''[[All Things Considered]]'', 24 April 2002.</ref> Coupled with his extremely high intelligence, these abilities have allowed him to achieve other distinctions as well, such as winning a statewide [[geography bee]].<ref name=geochamp />
Despite his young age and his autism, and even without formal instruction in musical composition,<ref name=NPRATC /> Savage is an accomplished musician and composer. He has released twelve [[album]]s as a solo performer, as leader of the Matt Savage Trio and as leader of various sized ensembles. By the age of 14, he had also performed with [[Chaka Khan]] and other popular singers.<ref name="CNN-0916-2006">''Genius: Quest for Extreme Brain Power'', [[CNN]] program hosted by Dr. [[Sanjay Gupta]], 17 September 2006.</ref> His compositions are very approachable and often humorous.{{Citation needed|date=November 2016}}
Savage has received many awards, including being signed in 2003 to [[Bösendorfer]] pianos. He is the only child to be so recognized in the company's 188-year history.
Savage has toured the world, performing for [[head of state|heads of state]] and others, and appearing on numerous television and radio programs such as ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', ''[[Late Night with Conan O'Brien]],'' ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]],'' and ''[[All Things Considered]]''. In 2006, at age 14, he was featured on a CNN report about the human brain, in which he was defined as a [[prodigious savant]], as opposed to the other types of [[savant syndrome|savants]].<ref name="CNN-0916-2006"/> Savage has also appeared in several documentaries about savants.
In 2007, he played with Scottish folk songwriter/singer Al Stewart, on piano. {{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}
In 2009, Savage enrolled at [[Berklee]] to continue advancing his musical career. The following year, in November, he prepared to release his ninth CD. {{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}
In December 2012, Savage received his B.M. in Performance (Piano) from Berklee College of Music.
In 2014, he composed and recorded the score for a full-length documentary film, ''Sound of Redemption: The Frank Morgan Story''.
In May 2015, he received his M.M. in Jazz Performance (Piano) from the Manhattan School of Music.
Currently, Matt balances his professional music career with teaching.
