{{Infobox military person | honorific_prefix = | name = Talhig of Shali | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = 250 | alt = | caption = Talhig of Shali. V. Shlipnev, 1920-early. | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | other_name = | nickname = | birth_date = unknown | birth_place = [[Shali, Chechen Republic|Shali]], [[Russian Empire]] | death_date = unknown | death_place = [[Shali, Chechen Republic|Shali]], [[Russian Empire]] | placeofburial_label = | placeofburial = | placeofburial_coordinates = | allegiance = | branch = | serviceyears = | rank = | servicenumber = | unit = | commands = | battles_label = | battles = | awards = | memorials = | spouse = | relations = | laterwork = | signature = | signature_size = | signature_alt = | website = | module = }} '''Talhig of Shali''' was a 19th-century Chechen commander.
In August 1845 he was appointed the leader of Greater Chechnya.
September 27, 1851 Baryatinsky defeated Naib Talhig Shalinsky at the village of Churtogay.
December 30, 1853 participated in the battle against the detachment of Major-General Baklanov in the village of Gordali.
September 28, 1854, together with Eski Mishchikovsky participated in the battle against the detachment Wrangel on the river Argun.
In 1859, he moved to the side of the Russian Empire. He wrote the chronicle in Arabic. Buried Talhig in the village of Shali.<ref name="ReferenceD">''Далхан Хожаев''. [http://zhaina.com/history/283-chechency-v-russko-kavkazskoj-vojne.html Чеченцы в Русско-Кавказской войне.] Издательство «СЕДА» 1998 {{ISBN|5-85973-012-8}}</ref>
